The full transition-probability matrices, giving the probability of moving from each state to
each other state over the interval from time zero, are available as the `transition_`
attribute for users who need them.

::: {.callout-note}
## Occupancy versus transition probabilities

Occupancy probabilities answer "what is the chance a subject is in state k at time t?". The
transition matrix answers the more detailed "given a subject in state j at the start, what is
the chance they are in state k at time t?". The occupancy probabilities are the initial-state
distribution multiplied through the transition matrix.
:::

::: {.callout-tip}
## Competing risks is a special case

A competing-risks model is a multi-state model with one initial state and several absorbing
states and no intermediate transitions. If that is your situation, use
[`AalenJohansen`](competing-risks.qmd) directly, which also gives standard errors for the
cumulative incidence.
:::

